{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583024/1921031101/0192.xml":{"full_text":"THE AGE-HERALD\nE. W. BAKKETT. lull tor\nEnter*1 at the Birmingham, Ala., post\noffice as second-class matter under act of\nCon grew March 8. 1878.\nSUBSCRIPTION HATES\nBy mail in United Stat es and Canadai\nBally and Sunday, year .$10.00\nBally, without Sunaay A.00\nBally aud Sunday, three months 2.70\nBally and Sunday, one month 1.00\nSunaay Age-lieraid, per annum 2.00\nBy Carrier In Greater Birmingham:\nBady ana Sunday, weak .26\nBally and Sunday, month 1.10\nBally and Sunday, year 13.00\nNo communication will be published wttn\nout its author's name. Rejected manu\nscript will not be returned unless stamps\nare enclosed lor that purpose.\nRemittances can be made at current rate\nof exchange. The Age-lieraia will not be\nresponsible for monoy seut through the\nmaiitt Address:\nTHE AGH-ULEKAEB,\nBirmingham. Ala.\nWashington bureau, ^oo Baviuaon buiiu- i\nlag. _ I\nEuropean bureau, 10 Ring street, Coveni j\nGarden, Condon, W. C. 2.\nEastern business office, World building,\nNew York city; western business of lice,\nTribune building, Chicago. The S. C. Beck\nwun special Agency, agents lor foreign\nadvertising.\nMember of the Associated 1'resa\n1 he Age-Herald is the only morning anu\nSunday newspaper m Birmingham carrying\nthe Associated Press dispatches.\nThe Associated iress is exclusively en\ntilled to the use for publication of ail news\ndispatches credited to It or not otherwise\ncredited in this paper aud also, the local\nnews published therein.\nAll rights of, repuoiicatiou of special dia\npatches herein' are also reserved.\nXEiJEPHoNE\nBell (private excuangs csoneetin*\ndepartments) Alain 48110.\nThough death be poor* it ends a mortal j\nwoe \u2014Richard II.\n\nA MORNING PRAYER\nIn the presence of manifold duties.\nLord, 1 have but one, and that to\nbe used by thee. If this one duty\nia done the lesser ones shall not be\nundone. Amen.\u2014Al. S. B.\nAmerica Still Playing\nthe Role of a Spectator\nEF recent events in Europe have?\nmade it unlikely that the Knox\nresolution to declare a separate peace\nwith Germany will be passed, Amer\nican honor has been saved.\nIt is evident that with the allied\narmies occupying German territory\nacross the Rhine the United States\ngovernment will be compelled to adopt\na foreign policy in conformity with\nthe new situation. American ttoops\nare still in the Rhine country, hold\ning the territory they occupied when\nthe armistice was signed. They will\nnot be withdrawn and they may pos\nsibly become involved in the repres\nsive measures adopted by the allies\nto make Germany live up to her war\nobligations.\nThe curious spectacle is presented\nof our late associates in the war mak\ning a concerted movement to collect\nindemnities from Germany while our\ngovernment simply marks time and\nour troops remain stationary, despite\nthe fact that our interests are al\nmost as deeply involved as those of\nEngland or France. It is a situation\nthat must exasperate Europe, as it\nis beginning to get on the nerves of\nthe American people.\nThe resumption of international\ntrade, the rehabilitation of Europe\nand the return of prosperity to Amer- j\nica all depend on a solution of the\nEuropean muddle. America ought to I\nbe active in this work instead of\ntwiddling her thumbs and like Wil\nkins Micawber, \u201cwaiting for something\nto turn np.\u201d Technically the allies,1\nwho have crossed the Rhine and may J\npenetrate deeper into Germany, are\nat peace with the country invaded.\nTechnically we are still at war with\nGermany.\nFurthermore, the contest between\nthe allies determined to make Ger\nmany pay, and a Germany which sul\nlenly refuses to meet their demands,\nmay continue indefinitely. In that I\ncase, what will be the attitude of the\nAmerican government? In such cir\ncumstances, we are certainly not go\ning to aid Germany, yet we are do\ning nothing to support the allies.\nAmerica Saves 3,500,000\nChildren in Central Europe\nABOUT four months ago the Lit\nerary Digest published a state\nment from Herbert Hoover that\n3,500,00 children in Europe would\nperish through cold, starvation, hun\nger and disease if they were not saved\nby the generosity of the American\npeople. That appeal did not go un\nt answered. The sum of $33,000,000\naske^ for, has been raised. The\n\u201cslaughter of the innocents\u201d will not\ntake place. The credit for this great\nachievement in humanitarianism be\nlongs to the Literary Digest which\ncarried the campaign through to sue-1\ncess, to Mr. Hoover and the great-!\nhearted American people who gave\ngladly that the innocent victims of the\nWorld war might not perish.\nThe response was immediate and j\nnation-wide. It seemed as if the peo- j,\npie of America said to themselves,\n\"Mr. Hoover knows what he is talk\ning about. He does not exaggerate.1\nIf he says 3,500,000 children in Eu-i\nrope will starve without our help, we i\nwill give it, and give it gladly.\u201d\nFrom every part of the United\nStates contributions were received.\nThe largest cities and smallest ham-\nlets answered the call of Europe\u2019s\nchildren. Donations ranged all the i\n/i-i?V\nway. fi*om the proverbial \u201cwidow's\nmite\u201d to millions of dollars, in lump\nsums. The American Red Cross, which\nf has done so ^nuch for the world, gave\n$5,000,000. It was literally a \u201cflood\nof live-saving gifts.\u201d\nThousands of -churches, of all de\nnominations, aided in this glorious\nwork. Funds were raised in school\nhouses from one end of yie country\nto the other. The Kiwanis clubs, the\nRotary clubs, Freemasons, Elks,\nj Knights of Pythias, Moose and all\nother fraternal societies bave their\nsupport, in addition to local chapters\nof the Red Cross, and .Junior Red\nCross, the Daughters of the Ameri\ncan Revolution and many other or\nganizations. Twenty-seven thousand\nnewspapers, including The Age-Her\ni aid, gave free publicity to the cam\n1 paign, through their editorial columns\nand otherwise. The motion picture\ntheatres did their part nobly. The\ncampaign was actively supported by\nthe following eight national organiza\ntions: The American Relief Admin\nistration, the American Red Cross,\nthe Federal Councils of the Churches\nof Christ in America, the Knights of\nColumbus, the Young Men\u2019s Christian\nassociation, the Young Women\u2019s\nChristian association, the American\nFriends\u2019 Service committee i$hd the\nJewish Joint Distribution committee.\nTruly it was a great' outpouring\nof American dollars for a sacred\ncause.\nOne Way to Alienate\nSouth American Tr*.de\nA DISPATCH from Monteviedo\nsays that \u201cmany merchants\nhave refused acceptance of American\ngoods consigned to them because, in-1\nstead of arriving boxed, as requested,\nthey came in bales and many of the\narticles were broken. Last night\u2019s\nedition of El Dia published photo\ngraphs of the broken, bales.\u201d\nThe paper goes on to say:\nSuch occurrences lead to strained\ncommercial relations between the\nUnited States and Uruguay, Uru\nguayan merchants hare received\nbetter treatment from .European\nmanufacturers who carefully fill\norders. The irritation which ac\ncumulated during the war when\nAmerican manufacturers took ad\nvantage of having no competition\nappears to be bearing fruit.\nThe buyer .has the right to name\nthe form of shipment. The manufac\nturer selling to a consumer who lays\ndown certain rules as to packing or\nother details of delivery is obligated\nto follow them as part of the con\ntract. If he does not conform, the\nconsumer has the right to reject the\ngoods, and he most assuredly has the\nfurther right to cease doing business\nwith that manufacturer and turn his\ntrade to those who do respect his\nwishes, i\nSenator John T. Morgan told us\nabout this 30 years ago. We must\ntrade with these people in the way\nthey wish to be traded with or we i\nwill not get the business. That is all\nthere is to it.\nForward Strides in\na Number of Lines\nTHE Alabama Power company is\ncompleting installing of a 20,000\nhorsepower unit at Lock 12 and will\nsoon complete the transmission line\nconnecting it with the Georgia sys\ntem, which, in turn, is connected with\nthose of Tennessee and Carolina.\nThe Louisville and Nashville rail-!\nroad is going ahead with a $30,000,\n000 improvement budget, In which are\nincluded pressed steel cars to be made\nat the new Chickasaw plant.\nThe Chickasaw pressed steel car\nplant, marking another forward step\nin steel production in Alabama, is on\nthe eve of beginning its useful ca- i\nreer.\nMoney invested in Birmingham cor- j\nporate enterprises during the first 1\ntwo months of the year has broken\nall prior records and set a pace\nnever before touched.\nThe February building permit rec\nord in Birmingham included 110 resi\ndences, which is 50 per cent more\nthan the monthly average for sev\neral years. Two high schools; a mar\nble postoffice, a Masonic temple, a\nYoung Men's Hebrew associa\ntion building, several churches and a\nnumber of industrial plants involving\nmore than $0,000,000 are under con\nstruction.\nAt Mobile the government is build\ning fuel oil and coal terminals.\nWe have just gollcn all-water rates\nfrom the east to Birmingham and\nother Warrior river pointy. Our trade\nwith the Pacific coast is steadily1\ngrowing and our steel exports con-;\ntinue large.\n\nGrowth of By-Product\nIndustry in Alabama\nALTHOUGH youngest in starting\nthe manufacture of by-product\nsoke, Alabama ranks already as the\nfourth state in the union in that in-!\njustry. The production of by-product I\ncoke in this state in 1920 was 3,075,\n000 tons, being exceeded onlyby Penn\nj sylvania, with 7,710,000; Ohio, with\n5,697,000, and Indiana with 4,567,000.\nAlabama is ahead of Illinois, New\nYork (the parent of the by-product\noven), Michigan and Minnesota, all\ni older states in the production of min\neral wealth.\nOf the 850 new ovens that went into\noperation in 1920, Alabama contribu\nted 334, the Tennessee company\nbuilding 154 additional, the Sloss\nSheffield 120 and the Alabama By\nProducts company 60. The increase\nin by-product coke manufacture in\nAlabama in 1920 was 845,000 tons, or\nnearly 40 per cent.\nEach ton of by-product coke means\ncheaper coke. Each ton of by-product\ncoke used in the manufacture of pig\niron represents a lower cost in the\nproduction of iron. There is an addi\ntional revenue from the sale of coal\ntar by-products and gas not utilized\nby the makers themselves.\nBy such means as these the Bir\nmingham district keeps to. the front\nand meets the competition of other\ndistricts. It requires genius of the\nsame caliber to successfully operate\nindustries in the south as in any oth\ner section. Natural advantages are\nbut a part of the business. Those\nwho rest on them get nowhere. The\nby-product industry has become a\nnecessary development.\nA raptured \"still\u201d and all its equip\nment was sold at a public auction in a\nFlorida town for 5 cents. It would\nhave brought mctfre at a secret sale con\nducted by some one not connected with\nthe sheriff\u2019s office.\n\nA woman member of the Kansas leg\nislature would tax old maids. Better\ncall them \"bachelor girls,\u201d unless wc\nwant to create a new class of tax\ndodgers.\nH*\nWith such a good example set by the\nrecent inauguration, all the graduation\ng\u00bbwns this year ought to be severely\nsimple and all the commencement ora\ntors should limit themselves to 30 min\nutes.\n\nThus Car the French have not insist\ned on having the satisfaction of march\ning into Berlin. See histories of Fran\nco-Prussian war.\n\nHenry Ford says the worst is over.\nHe was referring, of course, to the sit\nuation in America. Europe has not\nsven begun to see daylight yet.\n\nNow that an Indian chief has made\na successful debut in grand opera, some\none may \u201cdiscover\u201d an Eskimo who can\n*ing.\n\nPossibly Mr. Hoover suspected that\nifter he entered the Harding cabinet ne\nwould become, as it were, a bone of\ncontention.\n\nWhen a thousand coolies, more or\ness, are drowned in a shipwreck a\n>aragraph tells the story. The coolie\ns the cheapest form of human life.\n\nMr. Hearst fears the tallies have made\ni blunder. The past few years have I\nllustrated the fallibility of human na-\nure.\n\nMr. Harding is said to like musical\nomedies. Woodrow Wilson, prior to\n917, had the same amiable weakness.\n\nThe Utah legislature has just had\nts fourth fist fight during the present\nession. A school of pugilism.\n\nWhen the soviet leaders have to flee j\nrom Russia it will be another case of\nall dressed up and no place to go.\u201d\nAt At X.\nMr. Kthel Barrymore will be permit\nted to see the children. Does that in\nelude a call on their beautiful mama?\n\nIn order to briny \u201cIrene\" up to <ttte\nthe song hit of the piece should be\nchanged to \u201cMy Harding Blue Gown.\" i\n\nThe cootie doesn't take up much\nroom, but he positively is not wanted\nin America.\n\nFor ambassador to Great Britain, we j\nneed a man whose head is level, but not\nflat.\n\nAny legal business submitted to Wil\nson and Colby will ^receive careful at\nlention.-\u2014 Advt.\n\nBeer may be used for medicinal pur\nposes. It was once considered a splen- j\ndid tonic in the spring.\n\nThe disengdnuous Teuton is trying\nlo see what passive resistance will do. f\nTHft\\ LOOK HD ALMOST HI >1 A\nFrom the N\\ o**lds Work.\nCount Witte. In the World\u2019s Work\nfor March tells of his experiences at\nthe Portsmouth peace conference:\nAt President Roosevelt's order sev\neral secret service agent:* were detailed\nto guard me. They looked, spoke and\nbehaved like gentlemeh. those Ameri\ncan sleuths. There was nothing to mark\noff these plain clothes men, from other\nmen on the street\u2014at least to a for\neigner's eye. In Kurope It Is very easy\nto recognize a secret agent. In rtt. Pe\ntersburg he dresses like an ordinary\nmortal, but you can spot him from afar;\nre wears a stiff hat and carries a large\nblack umbrella.\nDON'T MlsmCK lOt It PITY\nFrom the Tampa Tribunf.\nWe have no sympathy with this\n\u201cPity poor Germany\u201d slobbering whine j\ngoing over the country, propaganda\nfrom Germany. Pity the poor rent of\nlire world that today ip suffering: be\ncause of the hellish determination of j\nGermany to dominate mankind! 1\nI\nIN HOTEL LOBBIES\nAND ELSEWHERE\nLiurifchtly nn^ I nnaaifary\n\u201cI am heartily in sympathy with the\nmove to construct a new courthouse\nand new city hall,\" said Ed Bishop,\nreal estate man, \"The present court\nhouse is unsightly and unsanitary,\nwhile the city hall is anything but\n'beautiful. The sooner Birmingham\nbujlds a new city hall and new court\nhouse, the better off we will be from\na civic standpoint.\n\"I am also of the opinion that re\nmoval of either city hall or court\nj house from their present sites, en\n[abling commercial enterprises to builft\nj on the location, would help develop- j\niment of the central business district,\"\n_ 1\nrapid nnd Uniform*\n\"Uniforms have once more come to\nthe assistance of Dan Cupid,\u2019\u2019 says\nGeorge J. Reynolds, and the result\nhas been that many boys of the na\ntional guard who met. girls while oh\nduty in the strike zones, Have married\nthem since they have been discharge*\nfrom active duty.\n\"This has occurred not only once or\ntwice, but several times, and I think\nthe romance is created because one\nparty thinks the other party, which he\nor she likes very much, is in danger.\u2019\u2019\nWanted to ray Toll\n\"I waa much amused recently about\na lobby in The Age-Herald which told\nof a Tennessee boy, who admitted that\non his first trip to Nashville that when\nhe wanted to ride, on the street car he\ndropped his nickel into a letter box,\u2019\u2019\nsays Fred Phillips, \"but I have what 1\nthink Is equally a.a good a story on an\nother Tenner**\u00ae*: n, for when he was\nsent out with a truck to East Birming\nham, when he came to the Douisville\nand Nashville crossing near the Bir\nmingham Machine and Foundry com\npany, the towerman lowered^ the gates.\n\"My friend thought to get by with\nout paying, for up where he lives any\none who tells the tollkeeper that he ia\non his way to church goes free, so he\nyelled out, \u2018Gwine to raeetinY and\nwhen the gateman didn't, lift the out\nstretched arms he got out a quarter\nand ran up into the tower to pay the\noperator.\"\nStop and Go SIriui\n\u201cPedestrians are certainly complying\nwith the new traffic laws to a marked j\ndegree,\u201d said William Perry, \u201cbut 1\nhave seen a few who either won\u2019t no\ntice the stop and go signs or else re\nfuse to obey them. However, with ev\nery one observing these new regula\ntions it givetf Birmingham the appear\nance of the large eastern cities where\nthese laws are enforced most strictly.\n\u201cThe officers are now leaving the\nsigns turned one way long enough for\npeople to walk across the street and\nI believe that many accidents will be\nprevented by these new regulations,\nwhich everyone is praising.\u201d\nThe Way You See It\n\u201cThere is consolation to be gotten\nout of every occurrence, even the pain- i\nful,\u201d said Richard M. Johnston of the i\nAlabama Power company. \u201cI was re- j\ncently visitirfg friends in Columbiana\nand one of them related this:\n\u2018An old-fashioned negro was chop\nping cotton on a warm nay down on a\nShelby county farm. lie was half\nasleep and in that state did not ob- j\nserve the direction of his hoe as he\nshould. Result was the descent of the j\nblade of the hoe on his naked toe and I\nthe infliction of a deep and painful j\nwound,\n\u2018The negro curled up on the ground\nin agony and nursed his toe for some j:\ntime in sorrow and self-commiseration, j\nthen turned on the toe in anger and\ndisgust, exclaiming, \"Smant on, you ole j\nfool toe; smalit on, Just as much as 1\nyou please. Gord know it ain\u2019t hu-rt in' 1\nme much as it do you.\u2019\nThe liiTMt Place\n\u201cFor the livest place on earth today,\u201d j j\nsaid Charles Sumner, who has been\nthere, \u201cgo to Eldorado, Ark., the new\noil town. Roome in private houses i\nrent for $100 per month. People have\ncome there on trains an<l in airplanes.\nIn less than 00 days that beautiful lit\ntle city of 5.000 inhabitants has been\ntransformed into a wild maze of people\nseeking their fortune. Prank deposits j\nhave increased $3,000,000 m t>0 days.\n\u201cSome Birmingham people, including\nU A May. are irr the game there. R.\nI.. Crook of Birmingham ts president of\nthe I\u2019nited Oil corporation there.\n\u201cAlready loo derricks can be counted\nfrom the courthouse. Nothing like it i\nhas ever been seen before on the Amer-\nlean continent.\u201d\nS1NTHET1C RUBIES\nFrom the (Cleveland Plain Dealer. t\nSynthetic rubies are identical physi-\noally and chemically with natural ru- j\nCes in structure, hardness, color and j\nbrilliancy, and can be nwLnufactured to a\nany size Small chips are fused in a i\nflame and there is no limit to the po&- 11\nbIbltitles of the process. It was dis- j c\ncovered by a Swiss minister. t\nM KE UMA'KE SAYS\nEvery small boy believes that whei.\nhe grows up and has children of ins\nown, he'll never cut a pie into less than\nfour pieces. I\nIt doesn't take you long to discover\nthat the people who oast reflections are\nnot the brightest people in the world.\nNever try to prove to a man that he\nis wrong about anything. You won't\nsucceed in proving anything, and you'll\nmake an enemy out of him.\nWe imagine it must be pretty tough\nfor a man to discover that his di\nvorced wife is on the jury that is going\nto try him.\nt\no\ni 1\nj t\nj t\nu\nc\nIs*\nWhen you marry her she may be so c\nslender that you are afraid she might j a\nslip down the drain pipe of the batn- jt\ntub. Hut 10 years later the chances ate j _\nthat she will be too big to get into the j\nbathtub.\nThe re.'sou we have courts and Judges |c\nis because if you could place yourself\non trial yon would always secure an\nacquittal. \u20221\nThe most effective men in every com-\nmunity .4re those who make the lea.st\nnoise. s\nSomehow or otlidr. the fellow, who t\ntalks through his hat thinks it is up\nto him to laugh at the fellow w'ho talks\nthrough his nose.\nOur idea of an i unselfish husband\nwould be one who lets his wife read p\nthe paper fi^Rt. And there\u2018Ain\u2019t no s\nslch animal.. k\nIf we had blind asyltims for those a\nwho are blind to their own intereutj. J\nevery second building would be a blind\nasylum.\n(Copyright. 1921.)\nMEN, WOMEN\nAND THINGS\nif you ever get. tired of the movies,\nfed up on vaudeville, surfeited with mus\n\u00bb\u00abal extravaganzas, bored with grand\nopera, and unresponsive to the legitimate\ndrama, don't give up hope until you\nhave witnessed a \u201ccollege night*\u2019 per\nformance, put on by a lot of happy\nhearted girls.\nI confess that of late I have been \u201cott\nmy feed.'\u2019 so to speak, when it comes to\nthe bill of fare which the amusement\ncaterers are furnishing to the Birming\nham patrons of their joy restaurants, it a\nnot their fault, however, as the offerings\nin all lines have been unusually good this\nseason. It\u2019s just my jaded appetite from\nsurfeiting.\nNow, I know you will*be surprised when\nI state that if you find yourself in the\nsame fix and wish to return to normaJcy\nso far as the amusement world is con\ncerned, the best way to do so is to cut out\nthe highly spiced shows and take on a i\nsure enough to goodness amateur per- i\nformance, played and staged by purely j\nhome talent without the guidance or meci-\ndl:ng of any professionals. f\n\nI know it is the fashion for many the-\natregoers to turn up theJr nose at the\nmere mention of anything which smacks\nof amateur theatricals, but the more they\nbear the earmarks in acting, costuming, j\nstaging and directing the better I like\nthem, for to me the poorest exhibitions j\nof all is to see a company of semi-pro- j\nfessionals. I prefer to take my acting\nstraight, as some topers like to gulp j\ntheir w-hisky without diluting it witn j\nwater.\nI never like to see a show by home\ntalent go through without some hitch,\nfor it always adds to the excitement when\nthe curtain fails to go up or down prop\nerly, the scenes get mixed, the costumes\ncome apart, the actors forget their lines 1\nor the orchestra gets out of tune. Some\nthing. must go wrong to make it a real\nistic amateur affair, even though it near\nly breaks the heart of the stage man\nager and the cast.\n\nI never like to look at a programme,\nmd I much prefer not to know the plot\nDf a tragedy, the story of a comedy, or\nthe lines of an opera. I want to have\n-he pleasure of seeing the tragedy de\nvelop before my eyes, the comedy sur\nprise me with unlooked for situations and\nLhe opera charm me with its unimaginea\nscenes. I know this is not the orthodox\n<vay of regarding the repertoire of the\n:heatre and the opera as most playgoers\njesire to be familiar with the play, the\nIramatized books or the thread of the\nstory around which an opera Is built.\nNow. I had my wish gratified on \u201ccol\nege night\u201d at Montevallo, as the girls\n>f the Alabama Technical Institute and\nCollege for Women, gave what to me was\ni delightful exhibition of the thing 1 am\n:alklng about. I do not mean that much\nibility was not displayed both in the orig\nnality of the acts, the songs, the toasts\nind the stunts, for each and every one\npore evidence that they had not been\n\u2022opted from any source whatever, but\nsvere bom in the fertile brains of the j\ncollege lassies\nClever as was much of the acting anti\nhe staging ami the skits, there was just\nmough mishaps to keep the crowd on\nip toe and bubbling over with fun, and\n:o add to the expectancy of the occasion\n10 one knew what was coming next, ror\nhe various acts and stunts had been\nguarded with jealous care. It was one\nihow in which there was no programme,\nmet we had to wait for the president ot\nh honor board to make each announce-\nnent before we could even guess what\nve were about to witness.\n\nThe school had been divided into two\nides, the college colors, punpie and gold j\nlesignating the division. Heretofore it\nlad been a contest of classes on \u2022'college\nlight,\u201d but this being the twenty-tirtn j\ninniversary, it was thought best to make\nt a contest between larger units. ifiach\ntide rendered college songs, each side j\n;:ive toasts, each side recited poems,\ntch side pulled off stunts, and each sidej\n\u2022resented a play. It was up to the three\nudges to score each offering and then\nland their decision to me. and it was\nny job to present the prize.\nBelieve me. the rafters rang when 400\nrirls sang in unison. Believe me. some\n'f the stunts showed originality in\nhought as well as ingenuity in expres-\nion. I can't mention all, but in one or i\nhe plays, when the footlights were\nailed, three lovely red-headed girls took\nheir position on the outer edge of tne\ntage. and the drop curtaitf consisted or\nwo charming misses who held in front\nhem pieces of white cloth with appro\nbate letters, while the scenery was very\nnuch alive in the person of beautiful 1\noung girls who, like the dryads erf old,\nrere imprisoned in the trees.\nj\nIn another play there was a stage set-\nng showing the main building of the i\nchool. and the marvelous changes old y\nlother Time was enabled to make of tne j j\nliny, the illiterate, the fast, the slangy,\nnd the slovenly girl was most refresh-\nig. and made the audience wish that\ntransformation could be so quickly I c\none instead of requiring a college course 1\ndo iL The masterpiece ^yas th^ IStiSi\nT. i. C. W. .woman who would go i 1\nack to her community as the exemplar\nf all that was womanly. c\nI think the thing which most impressed\nle in the whole performance was the 3\nrit of one of the girls, who receiving\ner part late in the afternoon, had little 1\nme in which to commit it to memory.\na endeavoring to speak her lines rather t\nTan read them, from stage fright waft t\nliable to do so* but walkmg back, se\nll red the written words, came forward j j\nnd went through her part in order to\nand up for her side. I hope she in- J c\ntirnates the composite girl to be gradu- g\nted at commencement. The gir! who in f\nle face of what may seem failure by j\noise and will power wins the victory.\nGreatly as J was interested in the e\\ a\nsilent showing of those who took part f\ni the evening\u2019s programme. I was equalr fl\nas interested in the splendid body ot f\noung women, who. so lo speak,, stood Q\nu the side lines as rooters for their\ndes. 1 never saw a finer exhibition (St\nue sporting blood than was shown by\n\\e wearers of the purple, for when l\npened the envelope which was handed r\nme by. the three judges, and read: 1\nTwo votes for the gold and one for the N\nurple,\" the latter rose to their feet and\nave tnree cheers for the gold. It's a 8\nreat thing to be a good loser. 1 came\nway feeling that the college spirit was t\njnning high at Montevallo.\nADRIFT WITH THE TIMES\nMOST RARE\nA citizen is known to me\u2014\nI fear the only one\u2014\nWho\u2019s never spoken flippantly\nOf Mister Burleson.\nSPOILING A FIVE-FOOT KISS\n\"What\u2019s the gentleman having a\nheated altercation with the manager j\nabout?\u201d\n\"He says he wants to patronize the\nsilent drama\"\n\"Well, isn't this a movie house?\"\n\"Yea, but he says he can\u2019t stand the\ngroans and sighs of other patrons when\nthe hero and heroine clinch.\u201d\nQUITE DIFFERENT\n*T understand you called me a worth\nless loafer.\"\n\"I did not.\u2019*\n,rWhat did you say about me, then?\"\n\"I merely remarked to a /nutual ac\nquaintance of ours that in the gentle\nart of killing time you had no superior.\"\n\u201cWell, that's different\"\nWOULDN\u2019T ENTERTAIN\n\"The reception committee is greatly\ndisappointed.\"\n\"Why so?\"\n\"The motion picture comedian who\nis the guest of the citV condescended\nto accept a little applause, but he re\nfused to stand on his head.\"\nIDLE SPECULATION\nRemarked a man with wild and blood\nshot eye.\nWhose manner showed that he was i\nfar from well,\n\"I often wonder wh\u2019at^bootleggers buy\nOne-half as deadly as the sniff they\nsell.\"\nTOUOH FARE\n\"Is it true that the cannibais you've\nbeen visiting sharpen their teeth to a\nroint?\u2019*\n\u201cYes,\u2019\u2019 said the explorer, \"that's one\nof the tribe's customs/*\n\"And do they eat old and decrepit\nmembers of their own families?\"\n\"I\u2019m sorry to say they do/*\n\"Umph! Maybe' that\u2019s the reason why\nthey sharpen thcjir teeth.\u201d\nTHOUGHT SHE WAS A PARROT\n\"You are charged with being drunk\nand disorderly, sir.\u201d\n\u201cYour honor, there must be a mis\ntake somewhere. 1 had a few drinks,\nbut I\u2019m sure I wasn\u2019t disorderly.\u201d\n\"The young lady cashier who had\nyou arrested says you were poking\ncrackers through the brass b^rs of her\ncage and saying, 'Pretty Polly, pretty\nPolly/\nTRIUMPH OF FEMINISM\n\"I see where a woman preferred big\nblack cigars and chewing tobacco to\nher husband, so they separated.\u201d\n\"What do you make of that?\"\n\"It. looks to me like another Illustra\ntion of the \u2018newer freedom.'\nTIME TO KEEP COOL\n\"As I was coming home tonfght/\u2019\nsaid Mr. Dubwaite, \"I was held up\u2014\u201d\n\u201cMercy!\u2019\u2019 exclaimed Mrs. Dubwaite.\nBy a highwayman?\u2019\u2019\n\"No, by a traffic policeman.\"\n\u201cThen you didn\u2019t lose anything.\u201d\n\"Yes, I did. I lost my temper and\n[\u2019m now under bond.\u201d\nPAUL COOK.\nEXIT THE STRANDED ACTOR\nFrom the Baltimore American.\nHE stranded actor, that mime of\nmingled comedy and tragedy.\nwill become a thing of the past\nif a bill passes which has been intro\nduced in the Albany legislature, re\nquiring owners of theatrical compa\nnies going on tour out of the state to\nfile a bond for $250 for each person in\nthe company, and if the venture fails,\ncompelling the owner to pay each\nmember of the company money enough\nto take him or her back to the place\nof departure. As New York is, so to\nspeak, the theatrical capital of the\ncountry, this bill, if it becomes law.\nwill affect practically the theatrical\npopulation of the United States, and\ngreat will be that population\u2019s re\njoicing thereat.\nOne of the great complaints of the\nactors striking for their alleged rights\nwas the ever-recurring possibility of\nbeing left strangers in a strange land,\nstranded, \u201cbroke,\u201d at the tender\nmercies of whoever would lend them\nmoney enough to get home or stake\nthem to a meal, when tae show fell\ndown, crushing hopes and prospects in\nane dismal heap. Of course, this hap\npened usually with the speculators and\nirresponsible plungers in dramatic\nanterprises, who traded on the cre\ndence of actors in their plausible prom\nises of a successful tour, or with iin\nI scrupulous managers and treasurers.,\nwho, seeing disaster, fled with wha:\nl could be 3aved from the wreck. In some\ncases it was honest misfortune. But it\nhappened often enough to make the\nstranded actor the object of that cheap\nhumor which has selected certain un\nfortunate types of human beings to\nchortle over with ghoulish glee whan\nmisfortune marks those types for its\nown.\nBut with such a law\" in force this\nhumor will become as dead as a tipsy\nscene in an up-to-date farce. No more\nwill the home-bound actor painfully\npound the ties to the jeering accom\npaniment of the printed ribald joker\nNo more will rural sheriffs impound\nunlucky Thespians till the latter are\nshorn of their last petty personal pos\nsessions. The show may close, but\nthe actors can \u201cexist\" to the nearest\nrailroad station with a Pollyanna feel- f\nin's; that it might be worse, much\nworse, and roll comfortably back to\nthe one and only Hialto.\nIncidentally, there is apt to be con\nsiderable flapping of angels\u2019 rings,\nwarily preparing to take flight from\nthe managerial traps set for their\ncatching, as the bond question looms\nup with its ominous suggestions for\nthe man who backs the show.\nTHE WHITE HOUSE DOG\nProm the Philadelphia Public Ledger. J\nTO the historic list of White\nHouse fauna there now is added\none high-stepping Airedale dog,\nejoicing in the nomenclature Caswel?\n^addie Hoy. That would do very well\nor a do^g show entry, but he will be\nailed Daddie for short. The White\nriouse wojild not be an American home\nf It were not the traditional abode of\n>ets. The widest and wildest variety\n\u00bbas in Roosevelt's time. Dogs and\ntorses figure largely among the dra\nnatis personae of the delightful \u201cDet\ners to His Children.\u2019' At one time\nhere were Jack the terrier, and\nlonathan, the piebald rat, and Archie's\n>ony Algonquin, which visited his\nlickroom, and a flying squirrel and\nwo kangaroo rats, besides a puppy,\ninnamed, but \"of the most orthodox\n)uppy type.\u201d There were Roosevelt\u2019s\niwn saddle horses. Renown and Blei\nitein in particular. The emperor of\nVbyssiriia sent a consignment of\nebras. lions and bauoons, which Mr.\ntoosevelt most reluctantly turned over\no the zoo.\nThe cow Pauline was an important\nnumber of the Taft entourage at\nVashington: She succeeded a cow that\nJeorge W. Childs of the Public Ledger\n\u25a0resented* to President Cleveland\nCharlie Taft\u2019s pony became a celebrity.\nIt will be recalled that in Lincoln's\nday little Tad was enamored of a\npair of goats which he drove in har\nness, and a letter from President Lin\ncoln describes bow one of the animals\nwas found calmly chewing its end in\nthe \\niddle of Tad\u2019s bed.\nPresident Wilson kept a fleck of\nsheep on the lawn\u2014bow different from\nthe intractable assemblage on Capitol\nHill! The White House grounds have\never been the favorite resort of birds\nof many species. Bluebirds, redbirds.\nwoodpeckers, flickers, grackles and\nrobins are much in evidence. In any\nadministration the birds have regarded\nthe purlieus of the President\u2019s home as\ntheir particular demesne. Squirrels are\nnumerous, and not less arrogant than\nthe birds.\nSo Laddie the Airedale comes to a\nplayground patted by the small feet of\nmany predecessors. If he knew where\nto look, there would be many old bones\nto^ig up. Now that the gates to the\ngrounds of the White House are again\nthrown open, he will have plenty of\nsociety\u2014\n\"Both mongrel, puppy, whelp and\nhound\nAnd curs of low degree.\u2019'\nHe will imitate the democratic\ngeniality of his master, and strive to\nbe nice to them alL\nDEMOCRATIC HOUSE LEADERS\n'rom the Washington Star.\nThe democratic House leadership has\nn the past 30 years been in the hands\nf John Sharp Williams. Joseph W.\niailey, Janies D. Richardson, Champ\n\u2019lark, Oscar Underwood and Claude\nfitchin.\nMr. Williams. Nfr. Bailey and Mr. Un\nerwood were transferred to the Sen\nte. partly as a reward for their House\nerviees. Ml. Bailey resigned from the\nenate. and Mr. Williams will retire\n,t the close of his present term. Mr.\n\u25a0nderwood is entering on his second\nerm. and is the democratic leader it.\nhat body\nMr. Richardson did not seek a seat\nn the Senate. He liked the House. and\nras one of the best parliamentarians\nn the floor. His leadership was unor\ntorical. He was argumentative and\nersuasive, and a quiet and skillful nc\notiator.\nMr. Clark was at once an orator, and 1\nrattling all-around debater. The en- i\nrgy of his floor leadership won the j\npeakership. When his party came into\nontrol he stood marked for promotion, j\nnd he was three times re-elected.\nMr. Kitchin is-on deck, though not in\nigorous health. The hope, shared by 1\nOth sides, is that his health may im\nrove, and enable him to take the par*\ni the new House for which he id so\n,ell suited. As was Mr. Clark, and\nomewhat on that order, he is an ag\nressive debater, has specialized on the\niriff, and stands for the old democ\nratic doctrine, a tariff for revenue\nnly.\n7'he democrats will be few in num\n\nber in the Sixty-seventh House. but\ncompetent leadership should en&bie\nthem to make a serviceable rec\nord for use in next year's congressional\ncampaign.\nTHIS SLOW LINK\nFrom the Cincinnati Enquirer.\nThe fussy m*ui was grumbling about\nthe slowness of the train he was riding\non. It was more than an hour late and\nwas crawling along in a nothing-to\nworry-about way.\n\"Hey.\u201d said the fussy man to the\nbr&keman. This is theblankety\nblankest no-count road in the world:\n\u2018\u2018Oh. it ain\u2019t so bad.\" defended ti\u00bbe\nbrakeman. \"I been on this road for 16\nyears, and\u2014\u2019*\n\u201cFifteen years!\u201d interrupted the fussy\nman. \u201cFor heaven's sake, what sta\ntion did you get on at?\u201d\nTHE HARDEJST TASK\nTed Robinson, in the Cleveland Plain\nOealer.\nWell, yoy have done a labor\nBoth difficult and long;\nI give you credit, neighbor\u2014\nYou\u2019re brave and strong.\nI honor men who shoulder\nA task, and put ir through.\nWhich other men, and bolder.\nRefuse to do.\nMen will plunge into danger\nWithout a frightened breath\nTo save a total stranger\nFrom threatened death.\nMen brake all malediction.\nAll sorrow, pain and loss.\nAnd march to crucifixion\nBearing their cross.\n1 hope my soul will let me\nI Endure what man endures\u2014\nBut. may Fate {never set me\nA task like yours.\nI should choose any other.\nNo matter where it led\u2014(\nYou went and told a mother\nHer t}on was dead!","height":"28272","width":"19864"}}
